  <description><![CDATA[<p>Sardinia is one of the largest islands in the Mediterranean, which means there’s plenty of coastline to discover. This is a haven for beach lovers – the island has more than we can count. Most of them have white sands and crystal clear water so it’s easy to think you’ve landed in the Caribbean. We recommend hiring a car and visiting as many as possible. The protected dunes of Chia are our favourite and you can hang out with the resident flamingos.</p>
<p>The sea is the main attraction in <a data-udi="umb://document/cc3361d2d7a945d38852da5e20516d75" href="/{localLink:umb://document/cc3361d2d7a945d38852da5e20516d75}" title="Southern Sardinia">Southern Sardinia</a>, with lots of natural landscapes and little coves to find. The <a data-udi="umb://document/10879313b41b457bb9a2212bd1747034" href="/{localLink:umb://document/10879313b41b457bb9a2212bd1747034}" title="Northern Sardinia">north</a> is much more glam. Porto Cervo is where you’ll find the jet-setting crowd with their super-yachts docked at the marina. Grab a glass of prosecco here and enjoy a bit of people watching. From the north you can jump on a ferry to Corsica or Isola Maddalena and get back to nature.</p>]]></description>
